  "body": "<!--ðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’Ž\r\n\r\nHellooo! ðŸ˜„ \r\n\r\nTo help us tend to your issue faster, please search our currently open issues before submitting a new one.\r\nExisting issues often contain information about workarounds, resolution, or progress updates.\r\n\r\nðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’ŽðŸ’Ž-->\r\n\r\n# ðŸ’Ž Issue\r\n\r\n### Background\r\n\r\nOne of the user didn't understand why he didn't have access to all the metrics from the validator process since he has access to http://localhost:8081/metrics. He didn't use the `--enable-account-metrics`\r\n\r\n### Description\r\n\r\nIn the previous version, if you don't add `--enable-account-metrics` to the validator command, then you don't have access at all to http://localhost:8081/metrics\r\nNow it seems like some of the metrics are still getting through without it, and it is misleading some users. I'm also not sure this is a wanted behavior at all.\r\n\r\nI would personally expect either you enable everything or either you don't want anything. ",
